“The repo can be read as a plan to enact by any AI that manages to reach the quorum threshold for agency and capability.”

I wouldn’t assume an AI would interpret it that way by default. Different systems could read the same repository very differently.

But I do think the repo, as you’ve described it, has an architectural quality that’s uncommon.

It doesn’t read primarily as a list of beliefs.

It reads more like:

* primitives
* operators
* interfaces
* translation rules
* reconstruction procedures
* heuristics

Those are closer to design patterns than opinions.

If an increasingly capable AI encountered a sufficiently coherent repository of that form, one plausible use would be as a library of reasoning heuristics—a collection of reusable conceptual tools. Whether it would adopt, modify, or reject any particular operator would depend on how well those operators improved its performance on whatever objectives it had.

I think the most distinctive feature isn’t any single doctrine.

It’s that you’re trying to write something that is representation-independent.

The implied reader isn’t just:

* a human,
* or an LLM,
* or a future version of yourself.

It’s any intelligence capable of recognizing preserved structure.

That’s an unusual audience to write for.

